Placed an order at 6pm, and expected delivery via Uber Eats between 7:45-8:15pm. All fine, except, every 10 minutes before the expected delivery time, the time kept getting pushed back. 8:05...it gets pushed to 8:30. At 8:20, it gets pushed to 8:55. At 8:45...pushed to 9:05. Then, at 9.15, my order gets cancelled. Can't tell if the restaurant or Uber Eats that failed. But either way, an utter failure.  It's one thing to be busy and have a long wait and delivery time. It's another to take on too many orders and push all of the orders they couldn't fulfill at the last second. Only at the end, to cancel them? How is that good business? Apologies to the Uber Eats driver that graciously waited for our food, but extremely unprofessional on both the restaurant and Uber Eats' part.  10/10 Will not be going back here when the world reopens.

I have been coming to this restaurant weekly for the past 6 months. At first, I LOVED it. The food was hot and delicious and the service was consistent. I’m sad to say it has been slowly declining over time. The service is very hit or miss lately. Some servers are very prompt and responsive. Others (one in particular) walk up to your table without greeting you or asking what you want and just stare at you. The last time I was there, I was seated outside and both tables on either side of me asked for a variety of things (their check, their drink, more chips and salsa) MULTIPLE times. I have noticed for some reason, that no matter who the server, they are stingy with chips and salsa (in particular). The salsa is served in a tiny cup that is typically used for ketchup or dipping sauce. This is something that is sort of expected at a Mexican restaurant and wouldn’t you want to eat the cost of this trivial item to serve more if it made your customers happy? Lately, the food has not been served hot and the order has been incorrect. I don’t know of the management changing lately, so I don’t know if they’re going through a rough patch or what, but I hope they restore themselves to their former glory because they have the potential to be an EXCELLENT restaurant!

One of my favorite spots, and I’m so happy it came to the neighborhood. Upshur St in Petworth is so hot right now, and this restaurant really helps step its game up.  Perfect for families with ample high chairs, plenty of roomy seating, and staff that are more than welcoming and excited to see us bring in our young son. There are many kids eating here with families (especially during early evenings), and there’s a great kids menu to feed them. Drinks come in little cups with a bendy straw to prevent spills, which is nice.  The food is also excellent. It feels pretty authentic for Mexico City, coming from someone that grew up in Southern California with a fantastic selection of all types of Mexican food. It fills a huge void in this city for true Mexican food. If you’re from California and miss the Mexican food options that just aren’t available on the east coast, give Taqueria Del Barrio a try. It’s close. So very close.  I’m a sucker for the cheese dip, and the amazing taquitos work well as a shared appetizer or even a main course. Try them either way. The guacamole is good, and the milanesa torta is my solid go-to when I’m not on a diet. It’s serious comfort food level.  There’s no carry-out,  but sit down and enjoy the food and a fantastic margarita out front on the patio when it’s a nice day.
